ts fluctuations and transformations in the semiotics of everyday life.Drawing on a set of thirty-three research interviews focused on disabled faculty members’ experiences with disability disclosure, as well as written narratives by disabled people, this book argues for the materiality of narrative, suggesting narratives as a means by which people enact boundaries around phenomena and determine their properties. Signs of Disability offers strategies and practices for challenging problematic and pervasive forms of “dis-attention” and proposes a new theoretical model for understanding disability in social, rhetorical, and material settings.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aPeople with disabilities. 0aSociology of disability. 7aHEALTH & FITNESS / Hearing & Speech.2bisacsh  aAgency.  aAttention.  aBook.  aCirculation.  aCollective.  aDeafness.  aDisability.  aDisabling.  aDisclosure.  aEmbodiment.  aEntextualization.  aEnvironment.  aEpistemology.  aEthics.  aFilter.  aImagination.  aInterview.  aMaterial.  aMateriality.  aMethodology.  aOntology.  aPerception.  aRace.  aResearch.  aRhetoric.  aSenses.  aSigns.  aStory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311075162840uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479811175.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479811175423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479811175/original  a978-3-11-075162-8  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_MDPM  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MDPM  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK